      <h2>Warning Signs You Shouldn't Ignore</h2>
      <p>Even if you follow a schedule perfectly, things can still go wrong. Be on the lookout for these red flags:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Flashing Check Engine Light:</strong> A steady light means "get it checked soon." A <em>flashing</em> light means an active misfire is occurring that can destroy your catalytic converter. Pull over immediately.</li>
        <li><strong>Grinding Brakes:</strong> Squeaking is often just a wear indicator. Grinding means the pad is gone and metal is scraping metal, ruining your rotors.</li>
        <li><strong>Sweet-Smelling Smoke:</strong> White smoke from the exhaust that smells sweet usually indicates a blown head gasket leaking coolant into the engine.</li>
        <li><strong>Vibrating Steering Wheel:</strong> This usually points to unbalanced tires, worn suspension parts, or warped brake rotors.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Seasonal Preparation</h2>
      <p>Depending on where you live, your car needs different care as the seasons change.</p>
      <h3>Winter Prep</h3>
      <p>Cold weather is tough on vehicles. Check your battery, as freezing temperatures severely reduce cranking power. Switch to winter tires if you live in a snowy climate—they use softer rubber compounds that grip ice better than all-seasons. Ensure your coolant mixture is correct to prevent the engine block from freezing and cracking. Finally, use winter-grade windshield washer fluid that won't freeze on the glass.</p>

      <h3>Summer Prep</h3>
      <p>Extreme heat is the enemy of batteries and cooling systems. Have your battery tested to ensure it hasn't been cooked by the heat. Check your air conditioning system and cabin filter. Most importantly, ensure your engine coolant is fresh and the radiator is functioning properly to prevent overheating during long summer road trips.</p>

      <h2>Maintenance Log Template</h2>
      <p>Keeping a log of your services is crucial for warranties and increases resale value. Use a format similar to this to track your work:</p>

